Program Goal 
Provide awareness and inspire computer science and related field university students to consider an 
AI-related career path. This program aims to accomplish that through a short introduction to the topic of 
machine learning. 
Facilitation Tips 
When presenting slides, try using live captions to assist users with hearing impairments. 
Do your best to understand the material, but it is ok to say, "I don't know" and point the learner 
towards the answer, for example, the TensorFlow documentation. 
The goal is to inspire and excite. 
Smile and enjoy yourself 
Share your experiences and set a good example 
Be aware of your Unconscious Bias (different learning styles, exposure to practical coding 
experience, etc) 
Encourage active learning: 
 
 
Explore ML | Page 1 
 
 
turn a lecture into a discussion, encourage everyone to participate. 
don't ask if they have any questions, ask what questions they have and wait while they think. 
empower participants to solve their own/one another's problems (resist urge to take keyboard) 
Learners have various levels of experience with machine learning, CS, and technology. 
Do your best to support each learner where they are at. 
Take time to explain jargon, concepts. 
If learners are advanced, encourage them to extend the project scope. 
Stick to the schedule 
Don't let the conversation become too detailed or abstract. 
The learners can access all of these activities on their own time 
Facilitator tips:  
Check your posture 
Vary your tone 
Avoid filler-words (like, um) 
Make eye contact 
Pause / Breathe 
Guidelines for Programming Activities 
Break learners up into groups of 2. 
The programming notebooks are designed to let the learners go through them at their own pace. 
Do not go through the slides as a lecture. These slides are for a debrief after the activity or to 
assist you in answering a learner's/class question. 
Students can save the Colab notebooks in Drive if they are signed into their Google account. 
Troubleshooting 
YouTube issues 
Check if you can access other websites. If possible, contact the site IT department to see if 
there is a network for professors, employees, etc. 
The videos are not essential to the course. If there are issues, encourage learners to watch the 
videos after class (perhaps on their phone) and you can summarize the main points if 
necessary. 
Feedback 
Give us feedback. How did this lesson work for you? Want to share a creative modification? 
Contact us at explore-ml-program@google.com.

Lesson 1: An Introduction to Machine Learning 
This is an introductory lesson into what Machine Learning is. The lesson introduces the three features that ML 
covers, classifying, clustering and recommending and links to the everyday examples for the learners.  
 
Learning Objectives 
Summarise what ML is. 
Distinguish between types of ML. 
Recognise when ML can be used to solve a problem.  
 
Instructor Prep 
Ensure the instructor computer has an internet connection with access to YouTube 
Ensure the learners computers have: 
Chrome installed 
An internet connection with access to g.co/quickdraw

Lesson 2: Neural Networks  
In this lesson, learners will begin to understand the basics of neural networks. By the end of the lesson, they 
should be able to summarise what is neural networks are and why they are so popular and powerful. 
 
Learning Objectives 
Explain what a neural network is and at high-level how it works 
Explore the effect of network structure on model performance 
 
Instructor Prep 
Ensure the instructor computer has an internet connection with access to YouTube 
Ensure the learners computers have: 
Chrome installed 
An internet connection with access to g.co/teachablemachine

Lesson 3: Group Presentations 
This lesson consolidates the learning from the previous four lessons and provides an opportunity for learners 
to investigate a particular area of ML in greater depth. Learners will be expected to put together a short 
group presentation about that area of ML and deliver it to the class. 
 
Learning Objective 
Articulate the ways in which machine learning is affecting different parts of technology and the 
ways it is having an impact on society. 
 
Instructor Prep 
Ensure you have all equipment ready beforehand. 
Ensure you are able to project your slides. 
Locate space in the classroom for post-its to be put on the wall (can also be done on a flat surface 
such as a table. 
 
 
60+ min. 
Group Presentations

Activity: Visual Thinking 
 
20 min. 
Group Activity: Create a 5 minute presentation 
 
20 min. 
Presentations (adjust time for number of groups) 
 
5 min. 
Closing Discussion, Next Steps

Lesson 1: Machine Learning Extended 
This lesson introduces the intermediate track. Learners will refresh their understanding of what machine 
learning is and some key terminology related to supervised machine learning models. 
 
Learning Objective 
Explain key terminology associated with supervised ML models. 
 
Instructor Prep

Lesson 2: ML Problem Framing 
This lesson introduces the basics of ML problem framing. Learners will gain a deeper understanding of how to

Lesson 3: First Steps with TensorFlow 
This lesson introduces TensorFlow to the learners. Any Explore ML sessions completed prior to this will 
support their understanding for this week.  
 
If prework is an option, learners can scaffold this lesson with an introductory video like Get started with 
TensorFlow. 
 
Learning Objectives 
Create and modify tensors in TensorFlow 
Learn the basics of pandas 
Develop linear regression code with one of TensorFlows high-level APIs 
Experiment with learning rate 
 
Instructor Prep 
Verify learners can access via the internet browser: 
https://www.tensorflow.org 
colab.research.google.com 
Ensure you are able to project your slides. 
 
 
Explore ML | Page 7

Activity Introduction Slide.

Lesson 4: Training an Image Classifier via Transfer Learning 
Learners will classify cats vs dogs images by using transfer learning from a pre-trained network. 
 
Learning Objectives 
Retrain a pre-trained model to transfer learning to a more specific classification task 
Evaluate the accuracy of a model based on test results. 
Improve a model by fine tuning parameters 
 
 
Instructor Prep 
Verify learners can access via the internet browser: 
https://www.tensorflow.org 
colab.research.google.com 
Ensure you are able to project your slides. 
Review the guidelines for programming activities and plan to let learners work 
in pairs after the Activity Introduction Slide 
 
 
60 min. 
Training Image Classifiers with Transfer Learning 
 
5 min. 
Introductions of instructor and classroom or other icebreaker 
 
10 min. 
Review TensorFlow. Introduce transfer learning and Pre-trained models 
 
40 min. 
Coding Activity: Image Classification with Fashion MNIST 
 
5 min.

Lesson 5: Building a Text Classifier with TF-Hub 
Learners will build a simple text classifier with TF-Hub, a library for reusing machine learning models. 
 
Learning Objectives 
Use TF-Hub text embedding module to train a simple classifier with a reasonable baseline accuracy.  
Analyze the predictions to make sure our model is reasonable 
Propose improvements to increase the accuracy 
 
Instructor Prep 
Verify learners can access via the internet browser: 
https://www.tensorflow.org 
colab.research.google.com 
Ensure you are able to project your slides. 
Review the guidelines for programming activities and plan to let learners work 
in pairs after the Activity Introduction Slide 
 
If time permits, let learners improve the model by: 
adjusting the estimator parameters 
following the suggestions in the "Further Improvements" section 
experimenting with other models in the " Advanced: Transfer Learning" section 
 
 
60 min. 
Building a Text Classifier with TF-Hub 
 
5 min. 
Introductions of instructor and classroom or other icebreaker 
 
5 min. 
Explain the task and TF-Hub 
 
40 min. 
Coding Activity: Building a Text Classifier with TF-Hub 
 
5 min. 
 
Closing Discussion, Next Steps 
Lesson 6: ML Lab: Captioning an Image 
Learners will combine their knowledge about machine learning and apply the skills gained from the previous 
coding activities in this capstone project. 
 
Learning Objective 
Build, train, and test an attention-based model to caption images. 
 
 
 
Explore ML | Page 9 
 
 
Instructor Prep 
Internet Connection 
Confirm data costs and speed - This project requires downloading a 13 Gigabyte dataset 
and training a model for an hour. 
Please remind learners of this in case they plan to use the notebook on their own. 
Verify learners can access via the internet browser: 
https://www.tensorflow.org 
Colab.research.google.com 
Ensure you are able to project your slides. 
Review the guidelines for programming activities and plan to let learners work in pairs after the 
introduction of the project.
